How to visualize data

Visualizing the data we’re working with is indispensible both to check that data pipelines are set up correctly and to check the predictions of a trained model. For visualization, the Makie.jl plotting package is used which requires you to install a plotting backend. Learning methods define how the data is visualized, allowing you to use the following functions for visualization:

  • FastAI.plotsample (plotsamples): Visualize an unprocessed sample (usually a pair of inputs and targets) or a vector of samples.

  • FastAI.plotxy (plotbatch): Visualize processed model input and output x, y or a batch of xs and ys.

  • FastAI.plotprediction (plotpredictions): Compare a model output with the ground truth.

To add support for these to a learning method, you have to implement the plotting interface, consisting of FastAI.plotsample!, FastAI.plotxy! and FastAI.plotprediction!.

Let’s look at an example using the Cat/Dog classifier from the saving and loading tutorial.

using CairoMakie; CairoMakie.activate!(type="png")
using FastAI

method, model = loadmethodmodel("catsdogs.jld2")
data = loadtaskdata(joinpath(datasetpath("dogscats"), "train"), ImageClassification)
mapobs((input = FastAI.Datasets.loadfile, target = FastAI.Datasets.var"#29#34"()), DataSubset(::FastAI.Datasets.FileDataset, ::Vector{Int64}, ObsDim.Undefined())
 23000 observations)

First we load a vector of unprocessed samples, a batch of training data and the corresponding model outputs:

idxs = rand(1:nobs(data), 9)
samples = [getobs(data, i) for i in idxs]
xs, ys = makebatch(method, data, idxs)
ŷs = gpu(model)(gpu(xs)) |> cpu
2×9 Matrix{Float32}:
 -2.10863   2.73647  -2.31912   1.19762   …  -2.30396   1.05854   1.18361
  2.6428   -5.06247   2.20946  -0.760145      4.2959   -1.84665  -2.35923

Then we can visualize the data with the functions listed above:

plotsamples(method, samples)
plotbatch(method, xs, ys)
plotpredictions(method, xs, ŷs, ys)

If you want to visualize data for your own learning methods, you can implement FastAI.plotsample!, FastAI.plotxy! and FastAI.plotprediction! to be able to use the above functions.
